	<article>
		<title>Getting Started with <pretext /></title>
		<subtitle>A Minimal Setup Tutorial</subtitle>

		<section>
			<title>Workspace Setup</title>
			<p>
				The quickest and easiest way to get started with <pretext /> is through GitHub.
				Using a GitHub Codespace means you don't need to install anything locally —
				everything runs in your browser with all dependencies preconfigured.
				Here's how to set it up:
			</p>

			<p>
				<dl>
					<li>
						<title>Create a GitHub Account</title>
						<p>
							<ol>
								<li>Go to <url href="https://github.com">GitHub</url>.</li>
								<li>Create an account (it's free for individual users).</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
					</li>

					<li>
						<title>Import the <pretext /> Codespace Template</title>
						<p>
							<ol>
								<li>Visit the official <url href="https://github.com/PreTeXtBook/pretext-codespace"><pretext /> Codespace</url> repository on GitHub.</li>
								<li>
									<p>
										<sidebyside widths="12% 38% 2% 24% 24%">
											<p>Click</p>
											<p><image width="100%" source="use-this-template.png"/></p>
											<p/>
											<p>and choose</p>
											<p/>
										</sidebyside>
										<q>Create a New Repository</q>.
									</p>
								</li>
								<li>
									<p>
										In the new window, fill in:
										<ul>
											<li><c>Repository name</c></li>
											<li><c>Description</c> — optional.</li>
											<li><c>Visibility</c> — choose <q>Public</q> or <q>Private</q>.</li>
										</ul>
										Then click <q>Create repository</q>.
										GitHub will copy the official <pretext /> codespace into your account as a new repo.
									</p>
								</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
					</li>

					<li>
						<title>Start Your Codespace</title>
						<p>
							<ol>
								<li>If you weren't automatically redirected, go to your GitHub account and open the new repository you just created.</li>
								<li>
									<p>
										<sidebyside widths="12% 18% 2% 68% 0%">
											<p>Click</p>
											<p><image width="100%" source="code-button.png"/></p>
											<p/>
											<p>and open the <q>Codespaces</q> tab.</p>
											<p/>
										</sidebyside>
									</p>
								</li>
								<li>
									<p>
										<sidebyside widths="35% 48% 17%">
											<p>In this tab, click</p>
											<p><image width="100%" source="create-codespace.png"/></p>
											<p/>
										</sidebyside>
									</p>
								</li>
								<li>
									The Codespace will begin setting up. This may take a few minutes the first time.
									When complete, you'll have a fully functional <pretext /> workspace running in your browser.
								</li>
							</ol>
						</p>
					</li>
				</dl>
			</p>
		</section>

		<section>
			<title>A Minimal Project</title>

			<introduction>
				<p>
					Once your Codespace loads, it'll will look like so: 
				</p>

				<image source="fresh-codespace.png"/>

				<p>
					It's ready for <pretext/>, but it needs a few files first. If you click on the <c>README.md</c> and scroll down to <q>Creating a New Project</q>, you'll find some directions for initiating a <pretext/> project.
				</p>
			</introduction>

			<subsection>
				<title>Creating a New Book</title>
					
				<p>
					<dl>
						<li>
							<title>Creating a New Pretext Project</title>
							<p>
								<ol>
									<li>Hit <c>F1</c> to open the command palette.</li>
									<li>Type <q>pretext</q>.</li>
									<li>Scroll down and select <q>PreTeXt: New Project</q>.</li>
									<li>Select the type of document you want to create. For this demo, we'll choose <c>book</c>.</li>
									<li>Select the location of your project, but the default should be the one you want.</li>
								</ol>
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>

				<p>
					Completing these steps will populate your codespace with all the files you need to author in <pretext />. In fact, it also provides a template that build right-away.
				</p>

				<image source="new-book.png"/>
			</subsection>

			<subsection>
				<title>Your First Build</title>
				<p>
					<dl>
						<li>
							<title>Building A Pretext Book</title>
							<p>
								<ol>
									<li>
										<p>
											Locate the <c>▷ PreTeXt</c> button on the bottom tool bar.
											<sidebyside>
												<p><image width="100%" source="pretext-button.png"/></p>
											</sidebyside>
										</p>
									</li>
									<li>To build the book, select <q>Build default target</q>.</li>
									<li>The default is the <c>html</c> version of the book. Let's also build a <c>pdf</c> version of the book as well.</li>
									<li>Click on the <c>▷ PreTeXt</c> button and select <q>Build Another Target</q> followed by the <q>print</q> option.</li>
									<li>The results of both of these builds should now be in the <c>output</c> folder.</li>
								</ol>
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>
			</subsection>

			<subsection>
				<title>Viewing the Output</title>
				<p>
					<dl>
						<li>
							<title>Viewing A Pretext Book</title>
							<p>
								<ol>
									<li>Now, we can view both the <c>html</c> and <c>pdf</c> version of the template book.</li>
									<li>To view them, click on the <c>▷ PreTeXt</c> button again and select <q>View Full Document</q> then choose either the <q>web</q> or <q>print</q> option.</li>
									<li>In either case, a new broswer window should open. If the <c>html</c> doesn't display in the broswer, try refreshing the page.</li>
								</ol>
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>
			</subsection>
		</section>
	
		<section>
			<title>Having A Look Around</title>
			<p>
				Once your Codespace loads, you'll see a ready-to-use <pretext /> project folder.
				You could begin writing immediately, but before doing so it's helpful to understand
				the structure and purpose of the key folders and files.
			</p>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Notable Folders &amp; Files</title>
				<p>
					<dl>
						<li>
							<title><c>source</c></title>
							<p>
								This folder contains your <pretext /> document files. Typically separated by chapter or section, plus a <c>main.ptx</c> file, which pulls them together.
							</p>
						</li>

						<li>
							<title><c>output</c></title>
							<p>
								The <c>output</c> folder is automatically generated when you build your project and contains the final product, ready to view or publish.
								You don't edit anything here.
							</p>
						</li>

						<li>
							<title><c>assets</c></title>
							<p>
								A general-purpose folder for supporting materials like images, data files, videos, etc. When you reference these in your source, <pretext /> includes them automatically.
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>
			
				<p>
					<dl>
						<li>
							<title><c>project.ptx</c></title>
							<p>
								The central configuration file that describes your entire project. This is where you specify the formats you want to generate and what files are needed to build them.
							</p>
						</li>

						<li>
							<title><c>main.ptx</c></title>
							<p>
								The entry point of your <pretext/> document that ties together all chapters or sections. It's like the <q>table of contents</q> of your project.
							</p>
						</li>

						<li>
							<title><c>publication.ptx</c></title>
							<p>
								This settings file that contains all the visual knobs for customizing the output of your documents.
							</p>
						</li>
					</dl>
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</section>

		<section>
			<title>Your First Build</title>

			<p>
				Now that you’ve explored the workspace, it’s time to build your first <pretext /> document.
				The template repository already includes a complete working example, so you can test the build process immediately.
			</p>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Building the Web Version</title>
				<p>
					<ol>
						<li>In your Codespace, open the integrated terminal (at the bottom of the editor).</li>
						<li>
							Type the following command and press <kbd>Enter</kbd>:
							<codeblock>pretext build web</codeblock>
						</li>
						<li>
							<p>
								The build process will begin. You’ll see messages as <pretext /> processes your source files, applies templates,
								and generates HTML in the <c>output/web</c> folder.
							</p>
						</li>
						<li>
							When the build completes, you’ll see a message indicating success.
							The generated files can be previewed directly in the browser.
						</li>
					</ol>
				</p>

				<p>
					This command produces a full-featured, navigable website with automatic numbering, cross-references, and MathJax-rendered equations.
				</p>
			</assemblage>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Previewing Your Output</title>
				<p>
					<ol>
						<li>In the Codespace file explorer, expand the <c>output</c> folder.</li>
						<li>Open the <c>web</c> subfolder, then right-click on <c>index.html</c>.</li>
						<li>Choose <q>Preview</q> → <q>Preview in Editor</q> to view it directly inside your Codespace tab, or select <q>Open in Browser</q> for a full window view.</li>
					</ol>
				</p>

				<p>
					You should now see a professional, interactive web page version of your document complete with a table of contents, equations, and styled sections.
				</p>
			</assemblage>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Building a PDF (Optional)</title>
				<p>
					<ol>
						<li>To generate a PDF version, use the following command:</li>
						<codeblock>pretext build pdf</codeblock>
						<li>
							<p>
								This will run a LaTeX-based build to produce a typeset PDF.
								The result will appear in <c>output/pdf/</c>.
							</p>
						</li>
					</ol>
				</p>

				<p>
					The PDF build may take a bit longer, especially the first time it downloads LaTeX packages.
				</p>
			</assemblage>

			<assemblage>
				<title>What’s Happening Behind the Scenes</title>
				<p>
					When you run a build, <pretext /> uses your <c>publication.ptx</c> file to decide:
					<ul>
						<li>Which outputs to generate (HTML, PDF, EPUB, etc.)</li>
						<li>How to apply templates, styling, and metadata</li>
						<li>Where to place the results (usually in <c>output/&lt;format&gt;/</c>)</li>
					</ul>
				</p>

				<p>
					Because everything is defined structurally rather than visually, your math, examples, and exercises automatically appear with consistent numbering and styling across all outputs.
				</p>
			</assemblage>

			<assemblage>
				<title>Quick Recap</title>
				<ul>
					<li><code>pretext build web</code> — generates a navigable HTML version of your document.</li>
					<li><code>pretext build pdf</code> — creates a typeset print version (optional).</li>
					<li>Outputs appear inside the <c>output/</c> folder — no manual file management required.</li>
					<li>All formatting, numbering, and linking are handled automatically by <pretext />.</li>
				</ul>

				<p>
					You now have a working build process and a functional document. 
					In the next section, we’ll explore how to edit content and customize your project.
				</p>
			</assemblage>
		</section>

	</article>

</pretext>